A ship captain's breakfast in Master and Commander: "a mug of small beer, hominy grits and cold beef". I believe "hominy grits" here actually refers to the American nixtamalized corn preparation even though at one point the word supposedly was used for oatmeal instead... "Peaty".

Not sure if Lyndon LaRouche knew this, but D. Galkovsky pointed out that in France Aldous Huxley's "Brave New World" was translated as "Le Meilleur des mondes", "The Best of The Worlds", referencing Pangloss parodying Leibniz's philosophy, tying the book with Voltaire's polemics.

I can't find much information about the translator (Jules Castier) but he's also responsible for translating Rudyard Kipling and Oscar Wilde into French and was involved with the Northern Railways that had a Paris-London train. It was probably not just a random guy's clever idea.
